Timelapse v0.1 -beta testing! I hope the installation worked!

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

About:

`timelapse` uses `ffmpeg` to generate timelapse videos from stills. If the 
timelapse.conf file is configured for an RTSP connection, `ffmpeg` is also
used to generate the still images from the stream.

`timelapse` can(should) be automated either using cron (see the cron*.example
files) or through systemd services (see the systemd .service and .timer files).
It can also be scripted to run stages manually if neither are an option.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Manifest of files installed from `timelapse`:

/
├── etc
│   └── timelapse
│       ├── Caddyfile.example
│       ├── cron.example-for-users
│       ├── README
│       ├── timelapse.conf-template
│       └── webgui
│           ├── index.php
│           └── style.css
├── lib
│   └── systemd
│       └── system
│           ├── timelapse.service
│           ├── timelapse.timer
│           ├── timelapse_fast.service
│           ├── timelapse_fast.timer
│           ├── timelapse_stills.service
│           └── timelapse_stills.timer
└── opt
    └── timelapse
        └── bin
            └── timelapse.sh

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
configuration (/etc/timelapse)


--->./Caddyfile.example:
    An example of a Caddyfile that could be used to serve the timelapse
    videos via Caddy (https://caddyserver.com) and PHP-fpm

--->./cron.example-for-users:
    An example of a user cron entry - Install this example file for the current
    user. From the '/etc/timelapse/' directory: 
    `crontab cron.example-for-users`

--->./crontab.example:
    An example of a system crontab - Install as the system crontab 
    (/etc/crontab) by running:
    `sudo cat /etc/timelapse/crontab.example > /etc/crontab`
    !!BE SURE TO CHANGE THE DEFAULT "changeme" USER TO YOUR ACTUAL USER!!

--->./README: This file

--->./timelapse.conf-template:
    A template file that should be used to configure how timelapse should run

--->./webgui/index.html:
    A VERY simple web page to display the videos

--->./webgui/style.css:
    A VERY simply cascading style sheet to give the HTML a tiny bit of fuss

-------
systemd (/lib/systemd/system)


--->./timelapse.service:
    A simple service to generate the timelapse video - This service should not
    be started manually. Instead, its corresponding .timer should be envoked.

--->./timelapse.timer:
    A timer that triggers (starts) the timelapse.service - Edit this file to
    configure how often your timelapse is updated. This timer should be
    enabled (with root priviledges) using 
    `systemctl enable timelapse.timer`

--->./timelapse_fast.service:
    A simple service to generate a faster version of the timelapse video - This 
    service should not be started manually. Instead, its corresponding .timer 
    should be envoked.

--->./timelapse_fast.timer:
    A timer that triggers (starts) the timelapse_fast.service - Edit this file 
    to configure how often your fast timelapse is updated. This timer should be
    enabled (with root priviledges) using 
    `systemctl enable timelapse_fast.timer`

--->./timelapse_stills.service:
    A simple service to generate the timelapse video - This service should not
    be started manually. Instead, its corresponding .timer should be envoked.

--->./timelapse_stills.timer:
    A timer that triggers (starts) the timelapse_stills.service - Edit this file 
    to configure how often to take stills for the timelapse. This timer should 
    be enabled (with root priviledges) using 
    `systemctl enable timelapse_stills.timer`


---------
the executabe (/opt/timelapse/bin)


--->./timelapse.sh:
    The main executable symbolically linked to /usr/local/bin/timelapse.sh for
    ease of use. Edit this script to your heart's content.
